data: {"type":"layer1","modelId":"local/apple-fm","model":"Crucible (offline)","text":"## Zod Schema for IPv4 Address Validation\n\n```json\n{\n  \"$schema\": \"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\",\n  \"title\": \"IPv4 Address\",\n  \"type\": \"object\",\n  \"properties\": {\n    \"ip\": {\n      \"type\": \"string\",\n      \"pattern\": \"^(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9]{2}){3}$\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"required\": [\"ip\"]\n}\n```\n\n## Explanation\n\n- **$schema**: Specifies the JSON Schema version.\n- **title**: The title of the schema.\n- **type**: The type of the schema, which is an object.\n- **properties**: A key-value pair where the key is the property name and the value is the schema for that property.\n  - **ip**: A string property that must match the IPv4 address pattern.\n    - **type**: String.\n    - **pattern**: A regular expression that matches a valid IPv4 address.\n- **required**: An array of property names that must be present in the input.\n\n## Validation\n\nThis schema validates an IPv4 address by ensuring that the input string matches the pattern of a valid IPv4 address. The pattern `^(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9]{2}){3}$` ensures that the address consists of four octets, each ranging from 0 to 255, separated by dots.\n\n## Usage\n\nYou can use this schema to validate IPv4 addresses in your applications. For example, you can use it in a form validation component to ensure that the input field contains a valid IPv4 address.\n\n```javascript\nconst { validate } = require('vee-validate');\nconst { toTypedSchema } = require('@vee-validate/zod');\n\nconst schema = toTypedSchema({\n  title: 'IPv4 Address',\n  type: 'object',\n  properties: {\n    ip: {\n      type: 'string',\n      pattern: '^(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9]{2}){3}$'\n    }\n  },\n  required: ['ip']\n});\n\nconst form = {\n  name: 'ip',\n  type: 'text',\n  rules: {\n    ip: schema\n  }\n};\n\nconst validateForm = (value) => {\n  return validate(form, value);\n};\n\nconsole.log(validateForm('192.168.1.1')); // true\nconsole.log(validateForm('256.256.256.256')); // false\n```\n\nThis example demonstrates how to use the schema to validate an IPv4 address in a Vue.js application. The `validateForm` function takes an input value and returns a boolean indicating whether the value is a valid IPv4 address.","done":true}

